{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"c365db24-80c9-4c47-ad1a-3edb83ff5f6b","content":"Run **`dotnet workload update`**. Here's why:\n\n- **`dotnet workload update`** — Downloads and installs the **latest versions** of all installed workloads to match your current SDK. After an SDK update, this is what brings workloads (like `maui`) back in sync.\n\n- **`dotnet workload repair`** — Re-installs workloads at their **current versions**. It fixes corrupted installations but doesn't upgrade anything, so it won't resolve version mismatches caused by an SDK update.\n\n**TL;DR:**\n\n```bash\ndotnet workload update\n```\n\nIf the build still fails afterward, try a clean + restore:\n\n```bash\ndotnet clean && dotnet restore\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"1023f96e-ba75-46ca-bf7f-fc634d8211e9","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about the difference between `dotnet workload update` and `dotnet workload repair` for fixing build issues after a .NET SDK update. This is a general knowledge question — I don't need to search any codebase for this.","outputTokens":240,"requestId":"980B:1A0B9E:159D9F5:1829112:6A051DE5"},"id":"43c2ed48-2a10-4a93-80b8-b7ff56438927","timestamp":"2026-05-14T00:57:16.484Z","parentId":"78e3c475-800f-4820-a2f9-c315a7493755"}
